{"author":{"id":"cff9ab1d2ee9741039b2a60d90cca378a5320ba753398f6f3df8d03abcebee1b"},"ops":[{"type":1,"timestamp":1773142229,"nonce":"Cz38sj+oGZ35sUfTMNPCdJJVFIE=","title":"Strong Parameters bypassed in multiple controllers","message":"Several controllers access user-submitted form data directly from params without using Strong Parameters (.require().permit()). This is inconsistent with the rest of the codebase and a potential security concern.\n\n## Affected controllers (5 instances)\n\n1. **CheckoutController#select_borrower** (line 29-30): accesses `params[:lending][:borrower_id]` directly instead of using the existing `checkout_params` method.\n\n2. **CheckoutController#update** (line 45): passes `params[:lending][:accessories]` directly to model, bypassing `checkout_params`.\n\n3. **CheckoutController#checkout_params** (lines 119-129): manipulates raw `params` object before calling `.permit()`. Antipattern that creates opportunity for manipulation before filtering.\n\n4. **ReturnsController#take_back** (line 35): passes entire `params` object to `LineItem.take_back(params)` without filtering. No Strong Parameters method exists in this controller.\n\n5. **ParentItemsController#create/update** (lines 62, 99): accesses `params[:parent_item][:all_tags_list]` directly, bypassing the existing `parent_item_params` permit list.\n\n## Secondary\n\n**UsersController#user_params** (lines 140-161): manipulates raw `params[:user]` before calling `.permit()`. Less critical since filtering eventually occurs.\n\n## Fix\n\nEach controller should route all user-submitted form data through a private `*_params` method using `.require().permit()`. Priority: CheckoutController (highest traffic) and ReturnsController (entire params passed to model).\n\nFound during review of PR #229 (Copilot comment #2).","files":null}]}